To validate this hypothesis from the outset, the PANGEA-HIV team simulated data under two highly complex HIV transmission and intervention models, whose components are considered essential for understanding long-term HIV transmission dynamics (
 Eaton et al. 2012). The aspects of HIV-1 spread evaluated here (
 table 1) were chosen both because molecular epidemiological studies into the sources of transmission and temporal changes in epidemic spread are in principle feasible (
 von Wyl et al. 2011; 
 Stadler et al. 2013; 
 Volz et al. 2013; 
 Dennis et al. 2014; 
 Ratmann et al. 2016), and because of their relevance to on-going HIV-1 prevention efforts in sub-Saharan Africa. Crucially, the model simulations were constrained to pessimistic and optimistic projections of the likely outcomes of on-going HIV-1 prevention efforts in sub-Saharan Africa (
 Iwuji et al. 2013; 
 Moore et al. 2013; 
 Hayes et al. 2014), as well as what sequence data could become available in these settings.
